= Abstract

The topology of an interbody fusion cage should provide early mechanical support while maintaining a mechanical environment favorable for postoperative bone ingrowth. Excessive stiffness may reduce mechanical stimulus in the surrounding bone, whereas insufficient material support may increase subsidence or local instability. The design task is therefore formulated as a constrained optimization problem coupling mechanical equilibrium, bone-density evolution, and spatial design variables.

This thesis develops a finite-element topology optimization model for the coupled cage-bone system. The cage design region, cortical bone, trabecular bone, and target ingrowth region are discretized by hexahedral elements under a small-strain linear-elastic assumption. A mechanical stimulus factor is constructed from element strain-energy terms, and a piecewise bone-remodeling law describes density formation, lazy-zone behavior, and resorption in the objective bone region. The multi-step density update is written as a discrete dynamical system. With terminal bone mass as the objective, the adjoint equation, adjoint load, density adjoint recursion, and design gradient are derived. The method of moving asymptotes is then used to update the cage material distribution under a volume constraint, forming a closed loop of forward prediction, backward sensitivity analysis, and design update.

The current manuscript focuses on problem formulation, mathematical modeling, discrete derivation, algorithmic procedure, and experimental design. Large-scale numerical experiments have not yet been completed; all final numerical values, contour plots, convergence curves, comparison errors, and result-dependent conclusions are explicitly marked as pending. The open computational implementation is treated as a reproducibility and audit mechanism for the mathematical model rather than the central scientific contribution.

Keywords: interbody fusion cage; bone remodeling; finite element method; topology optimization; adjoint method; method of moving asymptotes

